North America
---
Florida
- Cases. 13 Sep 2016. (confirmed [conf]) 79 locally acquired cases of which 70 are local residents, 9 are visitors; imported 720 cases of whom 86 pregnant.
http://www.miamiherald.com/news/health-care/article101659007.html

- Reporting. 10 Sep 2016. (disputed) Florida officials have: (1) Stopped providing detailed information on epidemiological investigations into local Zika infections; (2) Refused to identify all the locations where Zika-positive mosquitoes were trapped in Miami Beach; (3) and under-reported the number of local Zika infections in Florida by excluding anyone who is not a state resident. Florida's method for documenting local Zika infections adheres to standards set by the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention stating that Zika cases are counted in the state where the person lives -- regardless of where exposure might have occurred. Counting place of infection means there have been at least 64 local Zika infections in Florida this year [2016], not the 56 cases reported so far by the health department. http://www.miamiherald.com/news/health-care/article100939277.html

[Epidemiologically, it is more important to identify the locality where the infection was acquired in order to understand risk in specific geographic areas than the locality of residence of the infected individual. - Mod.TY]

- Mosquitoes, Miami. 10 Sep 2016. (announced) A new mosquito sample taken in Miami Beach tested positive for the Zika virus, the Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services announced on Fri [9Sep 2016], along with a warning from the mayor that the threat of Zika "continues to grow".
http://circa.com/politics/miami-just-found-more-zika-mosquitoes-and-congress-is-still-stuck-on-what-to-do-about-it

