Israel. 12 Sep 2016. (conf) 6 cases, ex Colombia 3 cases; Viet Nam, Dominican Republic and Mexico 1 case each.
http://www.timesofisrael.com/new-zika-case-reported-in-northern-negev/

[A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Israel can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4491053,90. - Mod.TY]

Japan. 13 Sep 2016. (reported) The patient was a 49 year old European woman who lived 1 year in Viet Nam. 3 days before presentation, she had rash on her chest. The day before presentation, she came to Japan for business, and her rash diffused on the face, trunk, arms, and legs. She experienced back pain, however, she denied having fever. On examination, she had conjunctivitis and maculopapular rash on her trunk and extremities. Blood tests revealed a normal white blood cell count (3510 cells/mcL) with slightly elevated monocyte (8.5 per cent) and normal platelet count (240 000 cells/mcL). Serum transaminase, createnine, and C-reactive protein were normal. The next day of presentation, she reported that her rash got light, however, both wrist joints were swollen with pain. Realtime polymerase chain reaction (PCR) test for dengue and chikungunya virus in her serum and urine were negative. Although real-time PCR tests for Zika virus in her serum and saliva on 3rd day after symptom onset were negative, real-time PCR tests in her serum on day 6 was weakly positive and in her urine on day 3 and day 6 were positive. Within a few days after onset, her symptom resolved.
(report provided by: Yuichi Katanami, Satoshi Kutsuna, Kei Yamamoto, Nozomi Takeshita, Kayoko Hayakawa, Yasuyuki Kato, et al. Disease Control and Prevention Center, National Center for Global Health and Medicine, Tokyo, Japan. <yuichi.katanami@gmail.com>)

[Dr Yuichi Katanami and colleagues are thanked for providing this report.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Japan can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4491053,156. - Mod.TY]

