[6] Neurological outcomes of infants
Date: November 2016 [ahead of print]
Source: Emerg Infect Dis. [edited]
http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/22/11/16-0956_article#suggestedcitation


Silva AAM, Ganz JSS, Sousa PS, Doriqui MJC, Ribeiro MRC, Branco MRFC, et al. Early growth and neurologic outcomes of infants with probable congenital Zika virus syndrome.

Abstract
We report the early growth and neurologic findings of 48 infants in Brazil diagnosed with probable congenital Zika virus syndrome and followed to age 1-8 months. Most of these infants had microcephaly (86.7 per cent) and craniofacial disproportion (95.8 per cent). The clinical pattern included poor head growth with increasingly negative z-scores, pyramidal/extrapyramidal symptoms, and epilepsy.

--
communicated by;
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

[The emotional, social, and economic impacts on the families from the long-term care that these infants will require are tragic. In an interview, Dr Neil Silverman, professor of obstetrics and gynecology at UCLA's School of Medicine and a member of the American Congress of Obstetrics and Gynecology's Zika Expert Work Group, who was not part of the study, said: "What is known for sure is that the children in the study, and others like them, will need lifelong services from specialists, including neuropediatricians, ophthalmologists, physiotherapists, nutritionists, nurses, and psychologists" (http://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2016/09/14/493791751/what-doctors-learned-from-42-infants-with-microcephaly). - Mod.TY]
